A kidney infection, also known as pyelonephritis, is a type of urinary tract infection (UTI) that specifically affects one or both kidneys. It's a more serious condition than a bladder infection (cystitis) and requires prompt medical attention.

Symptoms of Kidney Infection:

Symptoms can develop quickly over a few hours or days and may include:

Pain:
Pain in your side, back, or groin (often in the flank area, just below the ribs).
Pain may be dull, aching, or severe.
Fever and Chills: A high temperature (100.4°F or 38°C and above) and shivering are common.
Feeling Sick: Nausea and vomiting.
Changes in Urination:
Frequent urge to urinate.
Pain or burning sensation when urinating (dysuria).
Cloudy, dark, or bloody urine (hematuria).
Foul-smelling urine.
General Malaise: Feeling very weak or tired.
Loss of Appetite.
Diarrhea.
In young children, symptoms may be less specific and can include:

High fever.
Irritability.
Poor feeding.
Vomiting.
Lethargy (drowsiness).
Bedwetting (in previously dry children).
Cure of Kidney Infection:

The primary treatment for a kidney infection is antibiotics.

Antibiotics: Your doctor will prescribe a course of antibiotics, usually taken orally for 7 to 14 days, depending on the severity of the infection and the specific bacteria identified (if a urine culture is done). Common antibiotics used include ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin, co-amoxiclav, cephalexin, or trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole. It's crucial to complete the entire course of antibiotics, even if you start feeling better, to ensure the infection is fully eradicated1 and to prevent antibiotic resistance.   
