Pain Relief: Over-the-counter pain relievers like acetaminophen (paracetamol) can help manage pain and fever. Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) like ibuprofen are generally not recommended unless advised by a doctor, as they may increase the risk of further kidney problems.
Hydration: Drinking plenty of fluids, especially water, helps to flush bacteria out of the urinary system and prevents dehydration.
Rest: Getting enough rest allows your body to focus on fighting the infection.
In more severe cases or if complications arise, hospitalization may be necessary for:

Intravenous (IV) Antibiotics: Antibiotics are administered directly into a vein for faster and more effective treatment.
Fluid Management: IV fluids may be given to treat dehydration.
Monitoring: Closer monitoring of vital signs and kidney function.
Recovery:

You should start to feel better within a few days of starting antibiotics.
Most people recover fully from a kidney infection within about two weeks.
Follow-up urine tests may be done to ensure the infection has cleared.
Important Considerations:

Seek Medical Attention Promptly: If you suspect you have a kidney infection, it's crucial to see a doctor as soon as possible. Untreated kidney infections can lead to serious complications, such as kidney scarring, chronic kidney disease, high blood pressure, and sepsis (blood poisoning), which can be life-threatening.
Follow Doctor's Instructions: Take all medications exactly as prescribed and complete the full course.
Don't Delay Urination: Empty your bladder fully and regularly.
Hygiene: Practice good hygiene to prevent UTIs, which can lead to kidney infections. Women should wipe from front to back after using the toilet.
Stay Hydrated Regularly: Drinking enough fluids daily helps prevent UTIs.
